msContents.summary: This is an early sixteenth-century Italian manuscript by Domizio Calderino, which includes two texts: a treatise on the gods and a commentary on Virgil's Aeneid. The manuscript is made of five or six different paper stocks, one of which is of a smaller size. The initials of the first words in each text division are in large majuscules outside the text block.

msItem.title: Treatise on the gods, commentary on Virgil's Aeneid
msItem.author: Calderino, Domizio, 1447-1478

msItem.title: [Treatise on the gods]
msItem.incipit: Apud Aegyptios deorum genus primum fuisse fabulantur, nam conspicientes hunc mundi ornatum, admirantes quam universorum naturas duos esse deos et eos aeternos arbitrati sunt.
msItem.explicit: novum recentem et antiquissimum omnium, multo igni utentes, celerem motum facientem qui per alas et sagittas figuratur.

msItem.title: [Commentary on Virgil's Aeneid]
msItem.incipit: Cum Troiani et mari et terra agitati, sepulto Anchisa e Sicilia soluerent, ut in Italiam quae proxima et a fatis promissa erat, pervenirent Juno quae Carthaginem caput orbis facere instituebat.
msItem.explicit: vita anima, gemitu suspirio nam viro forti lachrimae non dantur, sed gemitus, sub umbras infernas. finis.
